<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-inner">
    <div class="badge"><span class="badge-dot"></span>2025 Pricing Guide</div>
    <h1 class="hero-h">Fractional CMO Cost:<br/><em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">What You Should Expect to Pay in 2025</em></h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">Real pricing ranges, what drives cost up or down, how to evaluate ROI, and Treetop's transparent starting-from rates. No games, no fake anchor pricing.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<section style="background:#0A1A0A;">
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">The Pricing Landscape</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Fractional CMO rates by engagement scope.</h2>
    <p class="sub">The range is wide because scope varies enormously. Here's how to read the market.</p>
    <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
      <table class="pricing-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tier</th>
            <th>Monthly Range</th>
            <th>Hours / Week</th>
            <th>Best For</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="tier-name">Strategic Advisor</td>
            <td class="price">$3,000–$5,000</td>
            <td>4–8 hrs</td>
            <td>Early-stage companies that need direction, not execution management. Limited strategic oversight only.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row">
            <td class="tier-name">Fractional CMO</td>
            <td class="price">$6,000–$12,000</td>
            <td>10–16 hrs</td>
            <td>B2B companies $5M–$30M with a small team to manage. Full strategy plus team/vendor oversight.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tier-name">Senior Fractional CMO</td>
            <td class="price">$12,000–$18,000</td>
            <td>16–24 hrs</td>
            <td>Larger teams, complex go-to-market, multi-product or multi-market companies.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tier-name">Heavy Engagement</td>
            <td class="price">$18,000–$25,000+</td>
            <td>20–32 hrs</td>
            <td>Near-full-time, typically companies $30M+ in active growth or transformation phases.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:#4A6A4A;margin-top:1rem;">Rates reflect 2025 U.S. market. Remote engagements run 10–20% lower than in-market. Rates for specialized verticals (fintech, healthcare, industrial) trend higher.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">Pricing Drivers</span>
    <h2 class="h2">What moves the number<br/>up or down.</h2>
    <div class="driver-grid">
      <div class="driver-cell">
        <span class="driver-label">Pushes Price Higher</span>
        <div class="driver-item up">Deep industry specialization (fintech, healthcare, enterprise SaaS)</div>
        <div class="driver-item up">Management of a large internal team or multiple agencies</div>
        <div class="driver-item up">Complex multi-channel demand gen (events, paid, ABM, content all running)</div>
        <div class="driver-item up">Board-level reporting and investor communications</div>
        <div class="driver-item up">Short-term urgency or active fundraise timeline</div>
        <div class="driver-item up">In-person presence required in a specific market</div>
      </div>
      <div class="driver-cell">
        <span class="driver-label">Keeps Price Lower</span>
        <div class="driver-item">Fewer hours required (strategy only, execution handled internally)</div>
        <div class="driver-item">Clear scope with well-defined deliverables</div>
        <div class="driver-item">Longer initial commitment (6+ month contracts)</div>
        <div class="driver-item">Remote-only engagement</div>
        <div class="driver-item">Small team, straightforward GTM motion</div>
        <div class="driver-item">Early-stage company with equity component</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section style="background:#0A1A0A;">
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">Equity vs. Cash</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Should your fractional CMO<br/>take equity?</h2>
    <p class="sub">Short answer: probably not if you're doing $5M+. Here's the full picture.</p>
    <div>
      <div class="step-row">
        <div class="step-num">→</div>
        <div>
          <div class="step-title">Equity makes sense at early stage</div>
          <div class="step-desc">Pre-revenue or seed-stage companies often attract fractional talent with equity + reduced cash. If you're capital-constrained and the CMO genuinely believes in the business, a 0.2–0.5% grant vesting over 2–4 years is reasonable.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-row">
        <div class="step-num">→</div>
        <div>
          <div class="step-title">Cash is cleaner once you have revenue</div>
          <div class="step-desc">At $5M+ ARR, most good fractional CMOs want cash. Equity arrangements complicate the relationship — misaligned on exit strategy, cap table concerns, vesting cliffs creating weird incentives at the wrong times.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-row">
        <div class="step-num">→</div>
        <div>
          <div class="step-title">Beware equity-heavy proposals</div>
          <div class="step-desc">A fractional CMO pushing hard for significant equity at your stage is either (a) not confident they can deliver measurable results or (b) not actually fractional — they want founder-level comp without founder-level commitment.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">ROI Framework</span>
    <h2 class="h2">How to evaluate if the cost<br/>makes financial sense.</h2>
    <p class="sub">Run the math before you sign. This is the framework we use with every prospective client.</p>
    <div class="roi-calc">
      <div style="font-size:0.75rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#4A6A4A;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Sample ROI Calculation · $10M ARR B2B Company</div>
      <div class="roi-row">
        <div class="roi-label">Current monthly pipeline (marketing-sourced)</div>
        <div class="roi-value">$500K</div>
      </div>
      <div class="roi-row">
        <div class="roi-label">Fractional CMO cost (monthly)</div>
        <div class="roi-value">−$9,000</div>
      </div>
      <div class="roi-row">
        <div class="roi-label">Conservative pipeline improvement at month 4 (15%)</div>
        <div class="roi-value">+$75K/mo added pipeline</div>
      </div>
      <div class="roi-row">
        <div class="roi-label">At 25% close rate, added revenue per month</div>
        <div class="roi-value">+$18,750/mo revenue</div>
      </div>
      <div class="roi-row">
        <div class="roi-label">ROI at conservative assumptions</div>
        <div class="roi-value green">2.1x in month 4, 5x+ at month 12</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#4A6A4A;margin-top:1.5rem;">Pipeline improvement of 15% at month 4 is conservative. Companies that haven't had marketing leadership before often see 30–50% pipeline growth. The real question: what's the cost of not having this?</p>
    <div style="margin-top:2.5rem;display:flex;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <a href="/fractional-cmo" class="btn-g">Fractional CMO Details →</a>
      <a href="/services/retainer" class="btn-g">Retainer Options →</a>
      <a href="/services" class="btn-g">All Services →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

